2.5. Finite element discretization
This section presents the finite element discretization of the governing equations (Eqs. (5)–(7)) that creates the basis for the developed simulation tool, which is implemented in Matlab®. Firstly, the threedimensional beam elements are presented. The Galerkin approach is then used to equate the weight function in the weak formulation, followed by a presentation of the element stiffness and mass matrices respectively. The proportional damping is introduced. Also, the external forces on each element are calculated followed lastly by the presentation of the discrete equations based on the preceding modeling. This section contains a large number of notations and some general notation rules are used to make the equations more understandable.
O.A. Nørve Eidsvik, I. Schjølberg Ocean Engineering 163 (2018) 322–336
325


The notation used in this section is as follows:
- Superscript i denotes element number i - Subscript i denotes node number i - Bold capital letters denote matrix.
It is assumed the cable is divided into a finite number of equal length elements, as indicated in Fig. 2. Each element has 5 degrees of freedom which results in 10 unknown states (6 deflections and 4 rotations). The deflections are denoted u,v and w for the x,y and z directions respectively and the rotations are denoted θy and θz for rotations about the y and z axes respectively. Eqs. (5)–(7) are written elementwise:
